<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="71cd6057f09b34426d1aced53249d173" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Tournaments rules and their application.<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.67)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=12149'>Patrick "CaptCanada" Malboeuf</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=12149&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> January 3, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Mike Girard raised some of the problems of the application of the rule against stalling in his last DGMA article, here is my response.<br />
 <br />
A lot of rules on LOTR are ambiguous because they rely on intention. Unless the player admitts it himself, there is no real way to prove stalling, scouting, or even colluding since it depends onthe itent the  player had, and not what actually happened.<br />
 <br />
When Michael Schumacher won a grand prix because his partner let him go ahead, a lot of people thought it was sort sort of cheating or at leastthat such a behavior should not be legal. That is a good analogy with colluding, and to a certain extent with stalling since the only way to make those actions illegal are by knowing for sure that they were intended.<br />
 <br />
In response to the harsh comments made about the FIA rules, the president of he FIA answered in an interview that the reason why there was no rule against what Ferrarri did was that because those rules would be unenforcable.<br />
 <br />
Even with that particular example, even with all the witnesses, if Schumacher`s partner said that he slowed down because of the pressure or because of a mopment of inattention, any member of the FIA could not contest that claim unless they knew what happened in his head. And until we develop some kind of mind reading machine, it is impossible to apply to rules unless the player or racer himself admits that he comitted a fault (which we cannot expect at such a high level and with such high stakes).<br />
 <br />
Because of those reasons, the only rules worth making are those we can enforce in any circumstance. In order to be clearer, here is an example I witnessed during the world cup:<br />
 <br />
Craig Berry of the USA was playing against Marcuss Rass of Germany in the ultimate match that would determine what country would advance for a top three stop and which wold be eliminated with a 4th place. I ccan assure you that there were a lot of spectators, including myself waching the match. At one point, Craig decided to assign his exhausted legolas to MArkus`s Ulaire Attea. Both resolved the skirmishes quite rapidly, knowing and legolas was on his way to the dead pile when Craig took legolas, removed the wounds from him but put him back on the table.<br />
 <br />
Markus didnt witness that since he was already tried to decide if he would move again and had assumed that legolas was on his way to the dead pile (after both players passing skirmish actions).<br />
 <br />
At that time, several spectators, including Roaln Benn, Marku`s partner were shocked and showed their discontent. A judge (who I don`t know the name unfortunately) took him aside, almost pushing him and said: show me in the rules where it is written that I can interact in a game unless a player asks me to. Of course Rolan had nothing to reply since it was true, the rules say that the judge cannot interact unless asked to.<br />
 <br />
Markus would latter doublemove to 9, making this issue irrelevant, but had he not, this event could have proven very very important.<br />
 <br />
After the game the decipher offiicilas took Craig Berry appart and gave him a warning (which basically has no concrete effect). This was unsatisfying to most since Craig`s supporters thought he had done nothing wrong and didnt deserve to be given any warning (since all the did was crumble to the tremendous pressure and forget something) and since his detractors thought that this action was too late, that he should have been stopped when it mattered: during the play.<br />
 <br />
Again,  this raises the question of intent: did Craig intentionnally put the Legolas back to increase his chances of winning? And because we have no way of knowing that unless we are on Craig`s head, we will never know. That is why we must assume that he did not do it on purpose and why it is considered as a mistake on his part. Dan Bojanowski has taken the (good) habbitof issuing warnings in such cases. If you receive two warnings in the same tournament, then you receive a game loss. While some say this is rather unjust I think it is the only way to realistically apply a rule to  those kind of behaviors. You are punished for your mistakes, as you would be in a game. This action doesnt assume that you made the mistake intentionnally, but that you did something illegal and thus a sanction must follow.<br />
 <br />
In that sense, the rule that allows Dan to give those warnings is enforcable, even if it contains weaknesses. For example, during day one of events, judgesare not able tosee each game at all times and thus cannot give all the  warnings that wold be deserved. High level players most of the time know when to call a judge but the vast majority of players will let it go, making the warning system rather weaker since it the fact that you receivea warning is not only based on what you do, but on the availability ofjudges and thepresenceof your opponent. A lot of player use this weakness to their advantage and take their chances, performing illegal actions and waiting if his opponent sees it. If no then they gain an advanatge and if their opponent indeed seesit they apologize and take back their actions. MOst players will not calla  judge to punish such an action, which makes the warning system a good idea, but lessened by it`s random application.<br />
 <br />
Since we are dealing with rules issues, here is another example: a player performs archery actions, forgetting to perform manoeuver actions, then realises he has forgotten them and says he will perform manoeuver actions. Of course his opponent calls the judge and he arrives, but the player starts to lie and says he has never said he would perform arcehry actions, that he was stil in manoeuver phase. The application of the rule here is hindered by the fact that judges are not always available to see all  matches and by the fact that not all players are honest. That is also a flaw in the application of the rule.<br />
 <br />
My point is that when the application of a rule is difficult, or random to make, one should challenge the rule itself. A lot of problems could be avoided by creating rules that do not create those kind of application problems.<br />
 <br />
I will conclude with my defense of the rule that did not allow the judge to ntervene in the BErry-Rass case.<br />
 <br />
The reason why this rule exists in my opinion is that if the judge is allowed to intervene whenever he wants, he will intervene when he sees mistakes, but since he his only a human he will sometimes miss some mistakes. That automatically means that because of the judge`s humanity, the outcome of the game will be shaped by the fact that he spots mistakes and forgets other mistakes. Surely,  there are enough factors in a game to manage for a player that we do not want the judge to be another one we cannot control.<br />
 <br />
That is why it must be th eplayer`s responsibility to call mistakes. The judge will thus act not as a player or an actor in the game, but as a reference, as a referee or a living rulebook.<br />
 <br />
If we gave the judges the responsibility to intervene whenever there was a mistake, we would give them a taskthey cannot perform since they too will miss mistakes. We cannot make a rule that asks judges to be perfect since it is impossible for them to perform.<br />
 <br />
In that sense, I think the judges a the world cup did a tremendous job, even although that one judge lost his temper when confronted to the angry Rolan.<br />
 <br />
HOwever, I still consider that the best judge I have ever encountered is Enrique Huerta. Enrique seems to care very little for rules when it comes to being fare. He takes every case one by one in order to restitute justice to the players and he has a natural flair doing so.<br />
 <br />
That is why Enrique will allow take backs when not allowing them would make an illegal action, or why he will not allow a player to perform an action when he sees the intent was to cheat the rules.<br />
 <br />
I myself have never contested one of Enrique`s decision (In fact I have contested very few judge decisions over myshort career) because even if I knew they weren`enbtirely following the rules, they were fair and just.<br />
 <br />
The danger with such a practice however is that not everyone will behappy with Enrique Solomon`s ( :) ) decisions and there are no appeals in his court.<br />
 <br />
In light of those observations, my personal conclusion is that in order to make the tournament scene more just, judges shold either follow the rules to the letter (making it fair and equitable to everyone) or should all go to a training session with Enrique (perhaps that would mean all players coming to a training session with me explaining them why they should not contest Enrique`s decisions).<br />
 <br />
Having experienced both the World Cup (where judges followed the rules to the letter and allowed illegal actions to happen rather than allwoing take backs) and the World Championships (where Enrique was the head judge) I can see advantages to both practices but if I get away from my personal thoughts and try to see rules as an impartial an objective thing,  I guess the solution would be to change the rules in order to make them more fair and not putthe responsibility on judges to restitute justice but rather on the rules themselves.<br />
 <br />
That is why rules that deal with intention should be completely removed. A better application of Dan Bojanowski`s warning system seems to me to be a good way to start.<br />
<br />
Of course this issue is opened to a lot of debating.<br />
